While Americans often debate the scale and duration of such programs, the majority view some form of unemployment insurance as a vital component of a stable democracy to prevent extreme hardship and ensure economic resilience. On a scale of 0 to 10, where 10 is an essential characteristic, the typical American response reflects a moderate-to-high valuation of this social contract.

